&gt; The question remains why console.log(&quot;3&quot;, data.uid); is undefined despite await before the setData.

Your arrow function in `useEffect` **captures** the `data` variable, and calling `setData` does not update the value of `data` in that function, whether or not you use `await`. How could it? `data` is declared `const`, so anything that sees it gets the initial value. The point of calling `setData` is to get a new value of `data` on the next rerender.

If you want a value you can change in `useEffect` and read immediately after, use `const data = useRef` and change the `data.current` field to the value you want.

P.S., you usually [shouldn&#39;t copy props to state](https://reactjs.org/blog/2018/06/07/you-probably-dont-need-derived-state.html#anti-pattern-unconditionally-copying-props-to-state). 

**EDIT:** Provided example

```javascript
const XYZ = props =&gt; {
  const data = useRef(null);
  useEffect(() =&gt; {
    const fn = async () =&gt; {
      data.current = 1;
      await delay(1000);
      data.current = 2;
      console.log(data.current); // 2
    };
    fn();
  }, []);
  return /* whatever */
};
```

There are couple of issues with the code:

* `setData` does not return a promise. Actually it does not return anything. So use `await` on it has no effect.
* In the effect function, you are calling `getInitialData` which is a async function but you are not waiting for its completion. 

Assumming that you want to fetch the user id on mount and then execute something once the user id is available, you can some thing like:

	const getInitialData = async () =&gt; {
		let user = await utils.getUser();
		setData({ ...data, uid: user.uid });
	}

	useEffect(() =&gt; {
		getInitialData();	
	}, []);

	useEffect(() =&gt; {
        if(data.uid) {
		     // whatever needs to be done once uid is available.
        }
	}, [data.uid]);

